very interesting: NOM schmeicheln ACC1 in ACC2 meaning NOM causes ACC1 to be in ACC2 by <schmeichel>ing. It is possible that this is not grammatical and the example (which sounds quite ok) is acceptable only due to some perfomance problem caused by the fact that schmeicheln is coordinated with two other verbs that select an accusative (cf. ?Er schmeichelte sie in den Boxclub). If it is grammatical, one may ask the question whether the sentence implies that he <schmeichel>s the children or whether it was also possible that he <schmeichel>s e.g. their parents. I'm not sure about that. But cf. Ich schmeichelte mich bis zum Abteilungsleiter. Sounds ok to me, accusative, I am not the person <schmeichel>ed.
"was" can either depend on wenig or refer to the proposition that there is not much to say about Servette. In both cases propositional (in the first case due to "sagen")
control in nominal context, anim because of control
